05934nam a22008655i 9780231545068DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017014876  a97802315450687 a10.7312/taba183662doi  a(DE-B1597)499048  a(OCoLC)1035213601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBP173.7b.T32 2018 4aBP173.7b.T32 2018 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a322/.109552231 aTabaar, Mohammad Ayatollahi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Statecraft :bThe Politics of Islam in Iran /cMohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Middle East Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Politics of Islam -- t1. The Factional Causes and Religious Consequences of Politics -- t2. A Shi’a Theory of the State -- t3. The “Islamic” Revolution -- t4. Institutionalizing Velayat-e Faqih -- t5. The Hostage Crisis: The Untold Account of the Communist Threat -- t6. Religion and Elite Competition in the Iran–Iraq War -- t7. The Metamorphosis of Islamism After the War -- t8. The Factional Battle Over Khomeini’s Velayat-e Faqih -- t9. Media, Religion, and the Green Movement -- t10. Historical Revisionism and Regional Threats -- t11. The Domestic Sources of Nuclear Politics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1979 revolution, scholars and policy makers alike have tended to see Iranian political actors as religiously driven—dedicated to overturning the international order in line with a theologically prescribed outlook. This provocative book argues that such views have the link between religious ideology and political order in Iran backwards. Religious Statecraft examines the politics of Islam, rather than political Islam, to achieve a new understanding of Iranian politics and its ideological contradictions.Mohammad Ayatollahi Tabaar traces half a century of shifting Islamist doctrines against the backdrop of Iran’s factional and international politics, demonstrating that religious narratives in Iran can change rapidly, frequently, and dramatically in accordance with elites’ threat perceptions. He argues that the Islamists’ gambit to capture the state depended on attaining a monopoly over the use of religious narratives. Tabaar explains how competing political actors strategically develop and deploy Shi’a-inspired ideologies to gain credibility, constrain political rivals, and raise mass support. He also challenges readers to rethink conventional wisdom regarding the revolution, Ayatollah Khomeini, the U.S. embassy hostage crisis, the Iran-Iraq War, the Green Movement, nuclear politics, and U.S.–Iran relations. Based on a micro-level analysis of postrevolutionary Iranian media and recently declassified documents as well as theological journals and political memoirs, Religious Statecraft constructs a new picture of Iranian politics in which power drives Islamist ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIslam and politicszIranxHistoryy20th century. 0aIslam and politicszIranxHistoryy21st century. 0aShīʻahzIran. 0aShīʻahzIran. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2018z978311065486808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBo